INTRO TEXT

Overall rates

Children were asked to select up to 5 items from the items below that they felt were most important for them to have a good life. The percentages in the chart below represent the proportion selecting each item.

Key finding: TO ADD

What combinations of items do children think are important

Percentages in chart below represent the proportion of all respondents that selected each two way combination of items as important to them having a good life. For example X% of all respondents select both Y and Z

Key finding: TO ADD

Which combinations are most correlated?

Figures in chart below represent the change in probability of a child saying an item was important to them having a good life if they picked another item. For example children who picked X are Y times more likely than other children to also pick Z

Note: red = stronger positive correlation (i.e. children selecting row are more likely to also select column in the chart below), blue = stronger negative correlation
